#Text=Bend
#Text=Bend
#Text=is the county seat of Deschutes County in Central Oregon .
#Text=Understand
#Text=The city of Bend , which is nestled between the Cascade Range and the Maury Mountains , is a tourist destination in summer and winter .
#Text=Visitor information
#Text=Bend Visitor Center
#Text=, 750 NW Lava Rd , Suite 160 ( At Oregon Ave ) , ☏ +1 541-382-8048 , toll-free : +1-877-245-8484 .
#Text=M - F 9AM-5PM , Sa - Su 10AM-4PM .
#Text=By plane
#Text=Redmond Municipal Airport
#Text=( Roberts Field RDM ) ( Terminal Bldg is on the west side of the airport runways .
#Text=It is accessed via SE Airport way . ) .
#Text=It is the major airport for commercial flights serving Redmond , Bend , Sunriver , Prineville and the surrounding communities in Central Oregon .
#Text=The airport is north of town along US Hwy 97 in the southeastern part of Redmond .
#Text=It is served by :
#Text=By car
#Text=Bend is served by U.S. Routes 20 and 97 .
#Text=From the west , U.S. 20 carries traffic from Santiam Pass and the Willamette Valley , and from Burns and southeastern Oregon .
#Text=U.S. 97 passes north-south through the city , carrying traffic from Klamath Falls to the south and the Columbia River Gorge and Yakima to the north .
#Text=To get to Bend from Portland , you can take U.S. 26 east from Gresham over Mount Hood to Madras where it meets up with U.S. 97 south , and follow U.S. 97 south through Redmond to Bend .
#Text=Or you can take I-5 south to Albany , then U.S. 20 east through Santiam Pass and Sisters .
#Text=Either way will take about three hours , not counting rest stops .
#Text=Both routes cross the Cascade Range and may receive heavy snow during the winter .
#Text=By bus
#Text=The main bus station for local public transportation and intercity buses is at the on NE 4th & Hawthorne ( 334 NE Hawthorne ) .
#Text=Bus stops for Cascades East Transit are lined up along NE Hawthorne and along NE 4th while the long distance buses are along NE 4th :
#Text=Cascade East Transit
#Text=Operates local public transportation and intercity buses to the surrounding cities/towns of Culver , Redmond , Madras , Metolius , Prineville , Sisters and Warm Springs from Hawthorne Station
#Text=CoBreeze
#Text=, ( bus stops ) Circle ' K ' @ 3405 N Hwy 97 ; Redmond Airport and Redmond Transit Hub , ☏ +1541 389-7469 .
#Text=Comes from Portland , Portland International Airport and Gresham via Sandy , Welches , Government Camp ( Mt Hood ) , Madras and Prineville P&R along US Hwy 26 .
#Text=Buses may not make all the above stops regularly but on request in advance of travel .
#Text=Check with them .
#Text=Grant County People Mover
#Text=Goes east towards Prairie City through Redmond Airport , Redmond Transit Hub , Prineville , John Day , Mitchell and Dayville .
#Text=There 's another route that goes towards Monument from Dayville .
#Text=Check schedules .
#Text=Mt Hood Teleporter
#Text=, ( Bus stop ) Hawthorne Station , ☏ +1541 903-0724 .
#Text=Goes up to Portland through Sisters and Salem via US Hwy 20/SR-22 and I-5 .
#Text=Passengers can transfer to Greyhound , Amtrak and other bus lines in Portland and Salem
#Text=Oregon Point
#Text=( Operated by MTR Western and Pacific Crest Bus Lines ) , ( bus stop ) Hawthorne Transit Center , ☏ +1888 846-4183 .
#Text=Tickets can be purchased through their website or through Greyhound.com :
#Text=Pacific Crest Bus Lines
#Text=Connects Bend to Eugene and Coos Bay .
#Text=Passengers connect to Amtrak and Greyhound ( Seattle-Portland-Sacramento route ) in Eugene
#Text=Get around
#Text=To fully enjoy the city of Bend , your best mode of transportation is the bicycle .
#Text=Bend has extensive bike paths and lanes and walking paths .
#Text=When visiting downtown Bend , you can park for free for the first two hours during business hours and unlimited hours after 5PM .
#Text=Downtown is best explored by foot .
#Text=Parking can be difficult at times but a spacious parking garage is located at the corner of Bond and Oregon Streets .
#Text=By bus
#Text=Cascade East Transit
#Text=provides limited bus service in and around Bend .
#Text=All buses stop at Hawthorne Station at fourth street and Northeast Hawthorne Ave.
#Text=See
#Text=High Desert Museum
#Text=, ☏ +1 541-382-4754 ext 271 ( weekday business hours ) .
#Text=Daily : May 1-Oct 31 : 9AM-5PM ; Nov 1-Apr 30 : 10 AM-4 PM .
#Text=The High Desert Museum is just south of Bend on Highway 97 .
#Text=The High Desert Museum is a great way to gain educational experience about some of the animals and habitat that go along with Central Oregon .
#Text=Historic Tower Theatre
#Text=, 835 NW Wall St ( Along NW Wall St between Minnesota & Franklin , downtown ) , ☏ +1541 317-0700 .
#Text=Smith Rock
#Text=Smith Rock State Park encompasses 651 acres on the Oregon high desert plateau which hovers around 3000 feet in elevation .
#Text=The park and campground are open year-round .
#Text=A $ 5 day use permit or a current state park camp receipt is needed for each vehicle .
#Text=A yearly permit is available for $ 30 .
#Text=Hiking trails offer spectacular views of the surrounding area .
#Text=You can spend 30 minutes walking along the river or a half day making a loop on the entire trail system that extends outside of the park .
#Text=The major rock faces are composed of welded tuff ( compressed volcanic ash ) reaching a height of up to 550 feet .
#Text=The picnic and campground areas sit on top of the rimrock which is made up of columnar basalt .
#Text=There are over 1400 climbing routes in and around the park ranging from some of the best sport climbs in the world to . “ Why would anyone want to climb that pile of choss ” .
#Text=People climb year-round , but summer temperatures can reach over , and in the dead of winter the thermometer stays close to the freezing mark ( ) during the day .
#Text=Spring and fall are the most popular climbing months .
#Text=Deschutes River
#Text=.
#Text=The Deschutes features ruggedly beautiful scenery , outstanding whitewater boating , and a renowned sport fishery for steelhead , brown trout , and native rainbow trout .
#Text=The Upper Deschutes features primarily flatwater boating with limited whitewater and excellent trout fishing opportunities .
#Text=The Middle Deschutes has excellent hiking opportunities with spectacular geologic formations and waterfalls , but boating is limited .
#Text=The Lower Deschutes offers the greatest opportunities for whitewater rafting and is one of Oregon 's premier steelhead and trout fisheries
#Text=Newberry National Volcanic Monument

#Text=South of Bend , See lava flows , explore lava caves and ice caves , fishing for trophy rainbow and brown trout in the two alpine lakes at the Newberry caldera ( East Lake & Paulina Lake ) and explore the massive Obsidian Flow .
#Text=There are hiking trails , camping and resorts .
#Text=Also snow parks , winter cross-country skiing and snowmobiling .
#Text=Visit the Lava Lands Visitor Center for information .
#Text=Cascade lakes and Mountains
#Text=.
#Text=These areas are spectacular .

#Text=Take a drive on the Cascade Lakes Highway and you can go to Sparks Lake , which is ideal for canoeing and kayaking , the Twin Lakes , Elk Lake and more while taking in some beautiful mountain scenery at the same time .
#Text=Many of these lakes offer fishing , camping , and trailheads for hiking up into the mountains .
#Text=Along the Cascade Lakes Highway , you can access trailheads as well as snow parks for snowmobiling in the winter .
#Text=Cultus Lake
#Text=.
#Text=About 45 minutes outside of Bend , Oregon , on the cascades lake highway .
#Text=At the lake there are a number of activities and facilities available for tourists , all centered around the crystal clear waters of the lake .
#Text=At Cultus
#Text=Lake there are a number of activities available .
#Text=The resort 's main attraction is its water sports .
#Text=One can rent a number of watercrafts including jet skis , motorboats , canoes , kayaks , paddleboats and party boats .
#Text=Gas and oil can be purchased on site .
#Text=Another popular activity at Cultus is the fishing .
#Text=The lake is filled with Rainbows , Bass , Mackinaws and Browns .
#Text=There are also beaches where people can swim and enjoy the water from another perspective .
#Text=At the lodge there is a restaurant open to the public .
#Text=They serve a wide variety of food here and it is reasonably priced .
#Text=One can also purchase groceries , although the selection is limited and prices higher than a supermarket .
#Text=Cabins are available to rent at Cultus Lake .
#Text=The cabins are near the lake , and have fireplaces , kitchens and appliances .
#Text=There are a number of campsites available on and near the lake . They are operated by the National Forest Service , and have a small per night fee .
#Text=There is running water , toilets and parking available to campers , however there are no R.V. hook ups .
#Text=Elk Lake
#Text=.
#Text=About 11 miles past Mount Bachelor and just a short drive out of Bend , Oregon .
#Text=It is known for its mountain scenery and relaxed atmosphere .
#Text=It has clear water , making it popular to people seeking water activities .
#Text=The Lake is 405 acres in size , with a depths ranging from 25'-75 .
#Text=The elevation of the resort is about 4884 ' .
#Text=At Elk lake fishing is a popular activity .
#Text=The lake is filled with Kokanee and brook trout .
#Text=In the summer months the lake is planted with brook trout .
#Text=Popular fishing techniques include : still-fishing , trolling and fly fishing .
#Text=Boating is also permitted at Elk Lake .
#Text=At the resort there are paddle boat , canoes , and sail boats available to rent .
#Text=Prices for these boats are fairly reasonable and can be checked out by the hour or by the day .
#Text=Larger motor boats are not allowed to help maintain the peacefulness on the lake .
#Text=There are a number of boat docks that surround the lake to make launching a boat relatively easy .
#Text=Swimming is easily accessible at the sunset and beach areas of the lake .
#Text=If hiking is your choice there are miles of trails that circle the lake .
#Text=At the resort there is a restaurant open to the public .
#Text=It serves a wide variety of food , specializing in their hamburgers .
#Text=For dessert they have a small ice cream parlor with about a dozen different flavors .
#Text=There is also a small store where groceries can be purchased .
#Text=Cabins are available to rent , and can be checked out at the main resort .
#Text=They vary in size and location .
#Text=Camping can be done at a number of different sites in the area .
#Text=The different sites include : Little Fawn Campground , Little Fawn Group Camp , Point Campground , and Elk Lake Campground .
#Text=There are also areas reserved specifically for day use .
#Text=Tumalo State Park
#Text=Day use $5/ vehicle , Tent site $ 21 , Yurt $ 46 .
#Text=Pilot Butte State Scenic Viewpoint
#Text=Free .
